---
import SidebarCard from '../components/SidebarCard.astro';
import ClassicShell from '../layouts/ClassicShell.astro';
import { SITE_TITLE } from '../consts';

const reviewChecks = [
	'The page has a clear reader problem and a useful answer.',
	'The title, description, headings, internal links, and structured data describe the same subject.',
	'The page adds practical judgment, examples, or decision criteria instead of repeating obvious advice.',
	'The page can be updated when the underlying website, publishing, or search guidance changes.',
];
---

<ClassicShell
	title={`Editorial Policy | ${SITE_TITLE}`}
	description="How OOCXX chooses, writes, reviews, and updates personal website and independent blogging guides."
	pageTitle="Editorial policy"
	pageIntro="OOCXX is written as a focused reference library for people building personal websites, independent blogs, and small editorial sites."
	introLabel="Policy"
	schemaType="WebPage"
	breadcrumbItems={[
		{ name: 'Home', item: '/' },
		{ name: 'Editorial Policy' },
	]}
>
	<Fragment slot="sidebar-top">
		<SidebarCard title="Primary Audience" eyebrow="Who">
			<p>
				Independent site owners, solo publishers, writers, makers, developers, and small teams that need
				a useful website before they need a large marketing operation.
			</p>
		</SidebarCard>
	</Fragment>

	<section class="section-block">
		<div class="section-head">
			<div>
				<p class="eyebrow">Purpose</p>
				<h3>Why these pages exist</h3>
			</div>
		</div>
		<p>
			The site exists to help readers make practical decisions about personal websites: what pages to
			publish, how to structure navigation, when to blog, how to name a site, and how to build durable
			organic discovery without turning the website into a pile of low-value pages.
		</p>
		<p>
			New pages should be created because they answer a real reader decision, not because a phrase looks
			available. If a topic cannot support a complete and useful answer, it should be merged into a
			stronger guide or left unpublished.
		</p>
	</section>

	<section class="section-block">
		<div class="section-head">
			<div>
				<p class="eyebrow">Method</p>
				<h3>How content is written</h3>
			</div>
		</div>
		<p>
			Most OOCXX guides use a decision-first structure: a direct answer, the conditions that change the
			answer, the mistakes that create weak websites, and the next internal pages a reader should use.
			This keeps pages useful even when a reader comes directly from search or another site.
		</p>
		<p>
			The writing favors small-site reality over generic marketing advice. A personal website usually
			needs clarity, trust, readable structure, useful writing, and good internal paths before it needs
			advanced optimization.
		</p>
	</section>

	<section class="section-block">
		<div class="section-head">
			<div>
				<p class="eyebrow">Quality Floor</p>
				<h3>What a page must pass before publishing</h3>
			</div>
		</div>
		<ul>
			{reviewChecks.map((check) => <li>{check}</li>)}
		</ul>
		<p>
			Pages that become thin, stale, duplicative, or search-engine-first should be updated, merged,
			redirected, or removed from prominent navigation. The standard is whether the page helps a real
			reader make a better website decision.
		</p>
	</section>

	<section class="section-block">
		<div class="section-head">
			<div>
				<p class="eyebrow">Updates</p>
				<h3>How pages are maintained</h3>
			</div>
		</div>
		<p>
			Pages should be reviewed when site structure guidance changes, search guidance changes, examples
			become dated, or internal links no longer represent the best reading path. Older pages may receive
			new dates only when the content has materially changed.
		</p>
	</section>
</ClassicShell>
